```css
/* Selector .btn--primary, declaration block in braces */
.btn--primary {
  background: #2563eb;
  color: #ffffff;
  padding: 8px 16px;
}

/* Higher specificity (id) overrides the class above */
#checkout-btn {
  background: #16a34a;
}

/* A disabled state the test must wait past */
.btn--primary:disabled {
  opacity: 0.5;
  cursor: not-allowed;
}
```
Here a button with id="checkout-btn" and class="btn--primary" renders green (the id rule wins on background), and while it is disabled it shows at 50% opacity and cannot be clicked — a test should wait for the :disabled state to clear.

```javascript
// Run these in the DevTools Console to validate locators against the LIVE DOM

// 1. Does this id exist and is it unique?
document.querySelector('#login-form');           // returns the element or null

// 2. How many products are on the page right now?
document.querySelectorAll('.product-card').length; // e.g. 12

// 3. Navigate a relationship: the price inside a specific card
document
  .querySelector('[data-testid="card-42"]')
  .querySelector('.price')
  .textContent;                                    // e.g. "$19.99"
```
Using querySelectorAll('.product-card').length before scripting confirms your selector matches exactly the nodes you expect, which prevents writing a test against a selector that silently matches zero or too many elements.
